(crowd laughing)

00:19:32.478 --> 00:19:34.138
So, that, I'd like to close with the idea

00:19:34.138 --> 00:19:36.683
that two, rare evolution maladaptions,

00:19:36.683 --> 00:19:39.112
this is just a theory for discussion,

00:19:39.112 --> 00:19:40.296
might have coincided to allow

00:19:40.296 --> 00:19:42.337
the mind over reality transition.

00:19:42.337 --> 00:19:43.527
Thank you.

00:19:43.527 --> 00:19:46.627
(crowd applauding)

00:19:46.627 --> 00:19:48.519
- In the 1860s or so,

00:19:48.519 --> 00:19:52.588
a Scottish essayist, and I'm
very fond of, Alexander Smith,

00:19:52.588 --> 00:19:55.360
wrote, "It is our knowledge
that we have to die

00:19:55.360 --> 00:19:57.108
"that makes us human."

00:19:57.108 --> 00:20:01.275
And, couple of decades later,
William James, in the 1890s,

00:20:02.370 --> 00:20:05.515
he'd called death "the worm at the core

00:20:05.515 --> 00:20:07.379
"of the human experience."

00:20:07.379 --> 00:20:10.752
And then, if we fast
forward a couple of decades,

00:20:10.752 --> 00:20:14.464
almost a century after that, in the 1970s,

00:20:14.464 --> 00:20:17.422
the cultural anthropologist,
Ernest Becker,

00:20:17.422 --> 00:20:21.560
he won a Pulitzer Prize for
his book, The Denial of Death,

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:23.569
in which he basically elaborated

00:20:23.569 --> 00:20:28.064
on that basic idea, it is our
knowledge that we have to die,

00:20:28.064 --> 00:20:29.740
that makes us human.

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:34.079
And he did so, by trying
to frame these ideas,

00:20:34.079 --> 00:20:38.166
in both an evolutionary,
as well as an existential,

00:20:38.166 --> 00:20:39.861
psychodynamic fashion.

00:20:39.861 --> 00:20:42.313
And what Becker does,

00:20:42.313 --> 00:20:44.162
even though this may sound a tad dated,

00:20:44.162 --> 00:20:45.323
given some of the ideas

00:20:45.323 --> 00:20:48.144
that we've already been exposed to today,

00:20:48.144 --> 00:20:50.107
is to just start with, I think,

00:20:50.107 --> 00:20:53.120
the relatively simple
Darwinian assumption,

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:57.116
that people are very similar
to all other forms of life,

00:20:57.116 --> 00:21:01.177
in that we're biologically
predisposed to survive,

00:21:01.177 --> 00:21:03.374
both in an interest of self-preservation,

00:21:03.374 --> 00:21:07.896
as well as reproducing, and
extending our chance overtime.

00:21:07.896 --> 00:21:11.191
On the other hand, Darwin
noticed, very early on,

00:21:11.191 --> 00:21:13.309
that there's lots of ways,

00:21:13.309 --> 00:21:15.251
over billions of years of evolution,

00:21:15.251 --> 00:21:18.110
that different forms of
life have accomplished,

00:21:18.110 --> 00:21:21.239
that most arduous task
of persisting overtime,

00:21:21.239 --> 00:21:23.340
so everything from the turtle shells,

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:26.762
to the eagle's eyesight,
and it raises the question

00:21:26.762 --> 00:21:28.487
of what is it,

00:21:28.487 --> 00:21:32.262
that is responsible for
our fantastic success?

00:21:32.262 --> 00:21:34.381
And the answer is there's lots of things,

00:21:34.381 --> 00:21:37.588
of both physical and psychological,

00:21:37.588 --> 00:21:40.920
including our relatively-large forebrain,

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:43.544
that gives us the capacity
to think abstractly,

00:21:43.544 --> 00:21:47.245
and symbolically, to
the point Becker notes

00:21:47.245 --> 00:21:50.092
that only human beings,
as far as we can tell,

00:21:50.092 --> 00:21:52.893
can imagine something
that doesn't yet exist,

00:21:52.893 --> 00:21:55.253
and then, have the audacity
to take our dreams,

00:21:55.253 --> 00:21:57.964
and render them into reality.

00:21:57.964 --> 00:22:00.004
Some of you have probably
seen a few head shakes.

00:22:00.004 --> 00:22:01.154
I know it's late in the day.

00:22:01.154 --> 00:22:04.323
Who's seen da Vinci's
drawings of helicopters

00:22:04.323 --> 00:22:06.143
in the 1500s?

00:22:06.143 --> 00:22:09.955
And when he did that, people
said, wow, that's crazy.

00:22:09.955 --> 00:22:12.601
And yet, today, we are
routinely transported

00:22:12.601 --> 00:22:14.409
by what was originally denounced

00:22:14.409 --> 00:22:16.650
as the doodlings of a madman.

00:22:16.650 --> 00:22:19.692
And so, abstract, symbolic thought,

00:22:19.692 --> 00:22:22.136
has certainly served us very well,

00:22:22.136 --> 00:22:25.429
and I like how Otto Rank, one
of Freud's disciples, put it,

00:22:25.429 --> 00:22:30.164
when he said that "Only human
beings make the unreal real."

00:22:30.164 --> 00:22:31.505
What Becker then does, though,

00:22:31.505 --> 00:22:34.416
is to move back in time,
a couple of decades,

00:22:34.416 --> 00:22:36.822
and to think about this idea in light

00:22:36.822 --> 00:22:41.052
of the Danish existential
philosopher, Soren Kierkegaard,

00:22:41.052 --> 00:22:43.565
and it was Kierkegaard who pointed out,

00:22:43.565 --> 00:22:46.342
that human beings are so smart,

00:22:46.342 --> 00:22:49.509
that we come to realize that we exist,

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:53.940
self-awareness, complex theory of mind.

00:22:55.134 --> 00:22:57.009
The way that Kierkegaard put it,

00:22:57.009 --> 00:23:00.631
it takes a ridiculously-sophisticated,
cognitive apparatus,

00:23:00.631 --> 00:23:03.061
to render yourself, the object,

00:23:03.061 --> 00:23:06.100
of your own subjective inquiry.

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:07.629
And what Kierkegaard did,

00:23:07.629 --> 00:23:10.259
in a little book called
Fear and Trembling,

00:23:10.259 --> 00:23:11.576
that I always recommend you buy

00:23:11.576 --> 00:23:14.665
for your in-laws' coffee
table, as a holiday gift,

00:23:14.665 --> 00:23:16.425
what Kierkegaard said,

00:23:16.425 --> 00:23:20.153
was that there are emotional ramifications

00:23:20.153 --> 00:23:22.972
of being explicitly self-aware.

00:23:22.972 --> 00:23:27.139
And he described them as being
both awesome and dreadful.

00:23:28.755 --> 00:23:32.665
Kierkegaard said, you know
what, it's really great

00:23:32.665 --> 00:23:36.255
to be self-aware, and to be alive.

00:23:36.255 --> 00:23:38.086
Who's ever had one of those magic moments,

00:23:38.086 --> 00:23:40.585
you wake up on a
beautiful day, like today.

00:23:40.585 --> 00:23:42.106
You didn't win a Nobel Prize,

00:23:42.106 --> 00:23:44.277
or you didn't win a great fortune,

00:23:44.277 --> 00:23:46.515
and yet, you're just
sublimely appreciative

00:23:46.515 --> 00:23:48.167
of the fact that you're alive.

00:23:48.167 --> 00:23:50.088
Everybody does look pretty happy today.

00:23:50.088 --> 00:23:52.157
(crowd laughing)
I grew up in New Jersey.

00:23:52.157 --> 00:23:53.460
So, it's a little dicier.

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:57.030
But, I think, for the most
part, we all understand,

00:23:57.030 --> 00:24:00.011
just the sublime and
spontaneous exuberance

00:24:00.011 --> 00:24:03.460
that comes from being alive,
and knowing that we're here.

00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:05.520
On the other hand, Kierkegaard
turns right around,

00:24:05.520 --> 00:24:10.396
and he says, yeah, but it's
also dreadful to be alive,

00:24:10.396 --> 00:24:14.304
and to know it, because less
GB, either a small child,

00:24:14.304 --> 00:24:16.215
or neurologically impaired,

00:24:16.215 --> 00:24:18.419
if you're smart enough
to know that you're here,

00:24:18.419 --> 00:24:20.459
you're also smart enough to know that,

00:24:20.459 --> 00:24:21.739
like all living things,

00:24:21.739 --> 00:24:24.180
your life is a finite duration.

00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:26.646
Moreover, you're smart enough to realize

00:24:26.646 --> 00:24:28.746
that your life could end in any time,

00:24:28.746 --> 00:24:32.145
for reasons that you could
never anticipate, or control.

00:24:32.145 --> 00:24:35.169
And that, from a purely
biological perspective,

00:24:35.169 --> 00:24:37.265
you're a breathing piece
of defecating meat,

00:24:37.265 --> 00:24:40.417
that is no more fundamentally
significant, or enduring,

00:24:40.417 --> 00:24:42.298
than a lizard, or a potato.

00:24:42.298 --> 00:24:44.399
And, what Becker argued,

00:24:44.399 --> 00:24:47.621
is that the explicit awareness

00:24:47.621 --> 00:24:50.160
of the reality of the human condition,

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:51.658
we will all someday die.

00:24:51.658 --> 00:24:54.059
We can die at any time.

00:24:54.059 --> 00:24:57.678
We're breathing pieces of
meat, cold cuts with attitudes.

00:24:57.678 --> 00:24:58.511
We're Spam.

00:24:58.511 --> 00:25:00.835
We're the plan boat, if you've got no can,

00:25:00.835 --> 00:25:04.668
would literally debilitate
us with paralyzing,

00:25:05.518 --> 00:25:07.439
existential terror.

00:25:07.439 --> 00:25:11.180
And what Becker proposed,
is that human beings

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:14.309
manage the terror that is engendered

00:25:14.309 --> 00:25:16.731
by the awareness of their mortality,

00:25:16.731 --> 00:25:18.648
by embedding ourselves,

00:25:19.583 --> 00:25:21.734
in what the anthropologists call culture,

00:25:21.734 --> 00:25:24.932
humanly-constructed beliefs
about the nature of reality,

00:25:24.932 --> 00:25:27.413
that we share with our
fellow human beings,

00:25:27.413 --> 00:25:30.340
that give us a sense
that life have meaning,

00:25:30.340 --> 00:25:32.119
and that we have value.

00:25:32.119 --> 00:25:34.911
And what Becker points
out, as an anthropologist,

00:25:34.911 --> 00:25:39.189
is that all cultures have
stories, or accounts,

00:25:39.189 --> 00:25:41.070
of the origin of the universe.

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:44.289
All cultures have prescriptions
for how we ought behave

00:25:44.289 --> 00:25:45.520
while we're here.

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:49.008
All cultures offer hope of
immortality, either literally,

00:25:49.008 --> 00:25:50.930
through the heavens,
souls, and afterlives,

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:52.930
of the world's great religions,

00:25:52.930 --> 00:25:54.790
or symbolically, through the belief

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:56.218
that while you may not be here,

00:25:56.218 --> 00:25:58.381
and I may not be here forever,

00:25:58.381 --> 00:25:59.832
we're comforted by the prospect

00:25:59.832 --> 00:26:02.662
that some manifestation of our existence

00:26:02.662 --> 00:26:05.712
will persist over time,
perhaps, from having children,

00:26:05.712 --> 00:26:07.892
perhaps, from amassing great fortunes,

00:26:07.892 --> 00:26:12.059
perhaps, from producing great
works of art and science.

00:26:13.486 --> 00:26:15.659
Moreover, what culture does for us,

00:26:15.659 --> 00:26:17.581
is to give us, each, social roles,

00:26:17.581 --> 00:26:20.080
with associated standards of conduct,

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:22.222
that if we meet, or exceed them,

00:26:22.222 --> 00:26:25.469
allow us to think that
we're persons of value,

00:26:25.469 --> 00:26:26.819
in a world of meaning.

00:26:26.819 --> 00:26:29.452
And when we do think
that way about ourselves,

00:26:29.452 --> 00:26:31.710
Becker called that self-esteem.

00:26:31.710 --> 00:26:35.689
His argument is that because
our beliefs about the world,

00:26:35.689 --> 00:26:38.960
and because self-esteem are so important,

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:41.451
that whether we're aware of it, or not,

00:26:41.451 --> 00:26:43.871
most of our behavior from day to day,

00:26:43.871 --> 00:26:48.350
is motivated in the service
of maintaining those beliefs.

00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:49.572
Alright, two questions.

00:26:49.572 --> 00:26:51.461
One question is, so what?

00:26:51.461 --> 00:26:55.592
And the other is question,
is any of this true?

00:26:55.592 --> 00:26:58.271
The so what question, in our world,

00:26:58.271 --> 00:27:01.708
is generally framed in
transit conceptual power,

00:27:01.708 --> 00:27:03.739
what is it that you could understand,

00:27:03.739 --> 00:27:07.905
if you momentarily accept the
voracity of Becker's claims,

00:27:07.905 --> 00:27:11.602
that it might be less easy
to understand otherwise,

00:27:11.602 --> 00:27:13.526
and then, the second question is,

00:27:13.526 --> 00:27:15.337
well is there any evidence,

00:27:15.337 --> 00:27:18.007
in support of these views?

00:27:18.007 --> 00:27:19.546
What we did, and when I say we,

00:27:19.546 --> 00:27:21.366
I mean, my buddies Jeff Greenberg,

00:27:21.366 --> 00:27:22.866
now, at the University of Arizona,

00:27:22.866 --> 00:27:25.917
and Tom Pyszczynski, now at
the University of Colorado,

00:27:25.917 --> 00:27:27.751
at Colorado Springs.

00:27:27.751 --> 00:27:31.278
We developed a very simple
laboratory paradigm.

00:27:31.278 --> 00:27:34.238
It's called the mortality
salience paradigm,

00:27:34.238 --> 00:27:37.155
and the logic, I think,
is disarmingly simple.

00:27:37.155 --> 00:27:40.545
We just said, alright, if
these ideas are correct,

00:27:40.545 --> 00:27:43.906
if our beliefs about
reality serve to mitigate

00:27:43.906 --> 00:27:48.279
death anxiety, well, let's
bring people into the lab,

00:27:48.279 --> 00:27:52.149
and let's remind them
that they're going to die.

00:27:52.149 --> 00:27:55.061
And in controlled conditions,
let's remind them,

00:27:55.061 --> 00:27:56.259
it's not as glorious as it sounds,

00:27:56.259 --> 00:27:58.774
let's remind them, in
controlled conditions,

00:27:58.774 --> 00:28:01.394
of something unpleasant, but not fatal.

00:28:01.394 --> 00:28:04.156
For students, think about your next exam.

00:28:04.156 --> 00:28:07.222
For regular people, think
about going to the dentist,

00:28:07.222 --> 00:28:10.130
and needing a root canal
without anesthesia.

00:28:10.130 --> 00:28:12.539
Think about being in a car crash,

00:28:12.539 --> 00:28:14.510
and having a limb amputated.

00:28:14.510 --> 00:28:18.301
All unpleasant, but
not particularly fatal.

00:28:18.301 --> 00:28:20.315
Alright, in our typical paradigm,

00:28:20.315 --> 00:28:23.366
we bury in a bunch of personality scales,

00:28:23.366 --> 00:28:24.808
two open-ended questions,

00:28:24.808 --> 00:28:26.640
"Please briefly describe the emotions

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:29.530
"that the thought of your
own death arouse in you,"

00:28:29.530 --> 00:28:32.192
and "Jot down, as specifically as you can,

00:28:32.192 --> 00:28:35.359
"what you think will happen
to you as you physically die."

00:28:35.359 --> 00:28:37.257
Alright, we do this in
a lot of ways, though.

00:28:37.257 --> 00:28:39.498
Sometimes, we go outside the lab,

00:28:39.498 --> 00:28:43.396
and we stop people, either in
front of the funeral parlor,

00:28:43.396 --> 00:28:46.258
or a hundred meters to either side,

00:28:46.258 --> 00:28:49.157
thinking that when you're in
front of a funeral parlor,

00:28:49.157 --> 00:28:52.507
death may be on your mind,
even if you don't know it.

00:28:52.507 --> 00:28:54.927
And then, the most subtle paradigm,

00:28:54.927 --> 00:28:57.426
we call it subliminal death primes.

00:28:57.426 --> 00:28:59.644
If you come to my office at Skidmore,

00:28:59.644 --> 00:29:02.195
you can your email, and
while you're doing that,

00:29:02.195 --> 00:29:06.154
we'll flash the word
death for 28 milliseconds,

00:29:06.154 --> 00:29:10.856
so fast, that you don't know
that you have been exposed

00:29:10.856 --> 00:29:13.236
to that rather unwelcome stimulus.

00:29:13.236 --> 00:29:14.815
Alright, so, that's what we do.

00:29:14.815 --> 00:29:17.866
All of these methods
produce the same outcomes.

00:29:17.866 --> 00:29:19.549
And so, let's briefly talk about

00:29:19.549 --> 00:29:21.787
some of the areas of inquiry.

00:29:21.787 --> 00:29:26.358
A lot of them, Ajit mentioned
earlier, in his fine talk.

00:29:26.358 --> 00:29:27.316
Alright, so what do we know,

00:29:27.316 --> 00:29:30.936
based on almost 40 years of research?

00:29:30.936 --> 00:29:33.568
Our original interest
was trying to understand

00:29:33.568 --> 00:29:35.908
why people can't get
along with other people,

00:29:35.908 --> 00:29:38.936
who don't share their beliefs
about the nature of reality.

00:29:38.936 --> 00:29:40.731
And what Ernest Becker said

00:29:40.731 --> 00:29:43.633
in a book called Escape from Evil,

00:29:43.633 --> 00:29:48.043
is that other people pose
an existential challenge

00:29:48.043 --> 00:29:49.941
to our belief systems,

00:29:49.941 --> 00:29:53.981
because if you accept an
alternative conception of reality,

00:29:53.981 --> 00:29:56.422
you do so, by undermining the confidence

00:29:56.422 --> 00:29:59.432
with which you subscribe to your own.

00:29:59.432 --> 00:30:03.252
And when you do that,
you undermine the beliefs

00:30:03.252 --> 00:30:06.622
that serve to minimize your anxiety.

00:30:06.622 --> 00:30:07.455
And what he proposed,

00:30:07.455 --> 00:30:10.285
is that when we run into
people who are different,

00:30:10.285 --> 00:30:13.344
the first thing we do is to
denigrate or belittle them.

00:30:13.344 --> 00:30:17.042
While we do that, we
simultaneously try to get them

00:30:17.042 --> 00:30:20.792
to get rid of their ideas,
and adopt ours instead.

00:30:20.792 --> 00:30:22.951
And if that doesn't work,
just kill those people,

00:30:22.951 --> 00:30:26.869
thus proving that my god
is better than your god,

00:30:26.869 --> 00:30:29.191
and we will kick your ass to prove it.

00:30:29.191 --> 00:30:31.142
Now, in support of that view,

00:30:31.142 --> 00:30:34.166
what we know in several hundred studies,

00:30:34.166 --> 00:30:36.154
conducted all over the world,

00:30:36.154 --> 00:30:38.782
by our people and independent researchers,

00:30:38.782 --> 00:30:42.822
is, for example, Christians
reminded of their mortality,

00:30:42.822 --> 00:30:45.187
they like fellow Christians a lot more,

00:30:45.187 --> 00:30:47.048
and they hate Jewish people.

00:30:47.048 --> 00:30:49.447
If you go to Israel,
and remind Jewish people

00:30:49.447 --> 00:30:52.170
of their mortality,
they love Jewish people,

00:30:52.170 --> 00:30:54.321
and they hate Arabs and Christians.

00:30:54.321 --> 00:30:56.344
Germans reminded of their mortality

00:30:56.344 --> 00:30:59.293
sit closer to fellow Germans,

00:30:59.293 --> 00:31:01.104
and they sit further away from people

00:31:01.104 --> 00:31:03.112
who look like Turkish immigrants.

00:31:03.112 --> 00:31:05.726
Iranians reminded of their mortality,

00:31:05.726 --> 00:31:08.807
become more supportive of suicide bombers,

00:31:08.807 --> 00:31:12.920
and more willing to become
a suicide bomber themselves.

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:15.007
In America, as you know,
we're very practical.

00:31:15.007 --> 00:31:16.646
We're not about to blow ourselves up,

00:31:16.646 --> 00:31:18.716
but we're happy to blow up other people.

00:31:18.716 --> 00:31:21.198
When we remind Americans
of their mortality,

00:31:21.198 --> 00:31:23.879
they become more supportive
of the preemptive use

00:31:23.879 --> 00:31:27.003
of biological, nuclear,
and chemical weapons,

00:31:27.003 --> 00:31:30.732
against countries who pose
no direct threat to us.

00:31:30.732 --> 00:31:34.899
Another area of inquiry,
for us, that's not funny,

00:31:36.328 --> 00:31:40.871
has been understanding
how existential anxieties

00:31:40.871 --> 00:31:43.561
have a radical effect on
political preferences.

00:31:43.561 --> 00:31:46.063
Max Weber, the German sociologist

00:31:46.063 --> 00:31:48.525
at the beginning of the 20th century,

00:31:48.525 --> 00:31:51.473
coined the term charismatic leader.

00:31:51.473 --> 00:31:54.507
He said that in times
of historical upheaval,

00:31:54.507 --> 00:31:58.065
and existential anxieties
are apt to be aroused,

00:31:58.065 --> 00:32:00.727
that we often embrace a certain kind

00:32:00.727 --> 00:32:03.925
of seemingly larger than life leader,

00:32:03.925 --> 00:32:06.117
who he called charismatic.

00:32:06.117 --> 00:32:07.455
And he said that, very often,

00:32:07.455 --> 00:32:09.896
these are people who believe to be,

00:32:09.896 --> 00:32:14.125
either divinely ordained,
or self-appointed,

00:32:14.125 --> 00:32:15.915
in order to rid the world of evil.

00:32:15.915 --> 00:32:18.086
And we got interested in this,

00:32:18.086 --> 00:32:21.909
in the aftermath of September 11th, 2001.

00:32:21.909 --> 00:32:24.904
Old-timers may remember
that in a three-week period,

00:32:24.904 --> 00:32:28.315
President George W. Bush
went from the least liked,

00:32:28.315 --> 00:32:31.627
to the most liked president
in American history.

00:32:31.627 --> 00:32:35.995
We did a lot of studies,
leading up to the 2004 election,

00:32:35.995 --> 00:32:40.137
where we showed that Americans
preferred Senator John Kerry

00:32:40.137 --> 00:32:44.087
to President Bush, in
a benign state of mind.

00:32:44.087 --> 00:32:47.355
However, when they were reminded
of their mortality first,

00:32:47.355 --> 00:32:49.645
they liked President Bush a whole lot more

00:32:49.645 --> 00:32:51.657
than Senator Kerry.

00:32:51.657 --> 00:32:53.076
Ditto, on this election.

00:32:53.076 --> 00:32:55.868
This summer, we found in several studies,

00:32:55.868 --> 00:32:58.980
that our respondents
preferred Secretary Clinton

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:01.090
to now-President Trump,

00:33:01.090 --> 00:33:05.133
when they were in a
psychologically-benign state of mind.

00:33:05.133 --> 00:33:08.520
However, when they were reminded
of their mortality first,

00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:09.910
their affection and support

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:13.835
for the President Trump
increased, and they now liked him,

00:33:13.835 --> 00:33:16.334
more than they did Secretary Clinton.

00:33:16.334 --> 00:33:17.332
Alright, let's keep going,

00:33:17.332 --> 00:33:21.294
and let's see how death
anxiety fosters an alienation

00:33:21.294 --> 00:33:25.265
from nature, and contempt
for the environment.

00:33:25.265 --> 00:33:27.923
John Locke, in the 1890s,

00:33:27.923 --> 00:33:29.473
in The Second Treatise on Government,

00:33:29.473 --> 00:33:32.306
pointed out that anything that's natural,

00:33:32.306 --> 00:33:34.712
it is of finite duration.

00:33:34.712 --> 00:33:36.825
And, of course, that's what we chafe at,

00:33:36.825 --> 00:33:38.814
and that may have been
the psychological impetus

00:33:38.814 --> 00:33:42.305
for the construction of the supernatural.

00:33:42.305 --> 00:33:44.177
And to the extent, that's true.

00:33:44.177 --> 00:33:47.710
When death is on our mind, we
should chafe at the prospect

00:33:47.710 --> 00:33:49.350
that we're animals,

00:33:49.350 --> 00:33:52.209
and we should be uncomfortable in nature.

00:33:52.209 --> 00:33:54.060
And that's exactly what we find.

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:56.985
People, who are reminded
of their mortality,

00:33:56.985 --> 00:34:00.890
that take issue with claims
that humans are animals.

00:34:00.890 --> 00:34:03.479
They have more negative
attitudes towards animals,

00:34:03.479 --> 00:34:05.327
and think it's okay to kill them,

00:34:05.327 --> 00:34:09.626
for reasons other than
food, and medical research.

00:34:09.626 --> 00:34:11.896
People reminded of their mortality,

00:34:11.896 --> 00:34:16.063
become more uncomfortable,
when they're out in nature.

00:34:16.943 --> 00:34:19.535
And people reminded of their mortality,

00:34:19.535 --> 00:34:22.406
become more willing to greedily exploit

00:34:22.406 --> 00:34:24.951
non-renewable natural resources.

00:34:24.951 --> 00:34:27.842
And, of course, we can't
talk about the plundering

00:34:27.842 --> 00:34:32.204
of the environment, without
a concurrent consideration

00:34:32.204 --> 00:34:36.371
of our seemingly insatiable
desire, for money and stuff.

00:34:37.414 --> 00:34:40.645
I like how Big Daddy in Cat
on a Hot Tin Roof put it,

00:34:40.645 --> 00:34:43.510
when he said, "The human
animal is a beast that dies,

00:34:43.510 --> 00:34:45.739
"and if he's got money, he
buys, and buys, and buys,

00:34:45.739 --> 00:34:48.940
"and I think the reason he buys
everything that he can buy,

00:34:48.940 --> 00:34:50.301
"is that, in the back of his mind,

00:34:50.301 --> 00:34:53.201
"he has the crazy hope
that one of his purchases

00:34:53.201 --> 00:34:55.218
"will be life ever-lasting."

00:34:55.218 --> 00:34:57.680
And research shows that Big
Daddy's right on the money.

00:34:57.680 --> 00:35:01.020
People reminded of their mortality,

00:35:01.020 --> 00:35:04.570
say that they have higher
fiscal aspirations.

00:35:04.570 --> 00:35:07.066
And they say it would take more money,

00:35:07.066 --> 00:35:10.152
before they would perceive
themselves as wealthy.

00:35:10.152 --> 00:35:13.550
People reminded of their
mortality want more stuff.

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:16.773
Not just any stuff, they want
high-status luxury items,

00:35:16.773 --> 00:35:18.940
like a Lexus, and a Rolex.

00:35:19.971 --> 00:35:22.404
When people are reminded
of their mortality,

00:35:22.404 --> 00:35:25.021
and you ask 'em to draw pictures of money,

00:35:25.021 --> 00:35:26.440
they draw bigger pictures,

00:35:26.440 --> 00:35:30.202
as if money looms larger,
when death is on their mind.

00:35:30.202 --> 00:35:33.981
And just giving people
money to count, not to keep,

00:35:33.981 --> 00:35:37.564
just counting money,
reduces death anxiety.

00:35:38.875 --> 00:35:42.596
If you like cookies, and
you're reminded of death,

00:35:42.596 --> 00:35:43.765
you eat more cookies.

00:35:43.765 --> 00:35:46.575
If you smoke cigarettes, and
you're reminded of death,

00:35:46.575 --> 00:35:47.724
you smoke more cigarettes.

00:35:47.724 --> 00:35:51.290
If you drink alcohol, and
you're reminded of death,

00:35:51.290 --> 00:35:53.207
you drink more alcohol.

00:35:54.275 --> 00:35:56.786
(stammers) Well, so,

00:35:56.786 --> 00:35:59.096
Thomas Hardy, one of my
favorite novelists, said,

00:35:59.096 --> 00:36:01.119
"If a way to the better there be,

00:36:01.119 --> 00:36:04.846
"it comes from taking a
close look at the worst."

00:36:04.846 --> 00:36:07.389
And just to follow up
on some of the things

00:36:07.389 --> 00:36:08.747
that Ajit talked about

00:36:08.747 --> 00:36:10.664
at the end of his talk,

00:36:11.655 --> 00:36:15.756
I would argue that
malignant manifestations

00:36:15.756 --> 00:36:17.936
of death anxiety,

00:36:17.936 --> 00:36:20.836
surely, do not bring out the best in us.

00:36:20.836 --> 00:36:25.111
They seem to turn us into
hateful, warmongering,

00:36:25.111 --> 00:36:27.543
proto-fascist, plundering the planet,

00:36:27.543 --> 00:36:29.581
in our insatiable quest for dollars,

00:36:29.581 --> 00:36:32.800
and draws in a television, alcohol, drug,

00:36:32.800 --> 00:36:35.049
Facebook, Twitter-induced stupor.

00:36:35.049 --> 00:36:36.991
And...
(crowd laughing)

00:36:36.991 --> 00:36:40.408
And Danny Brower might be right, in 2007,

00:36:41.912 --> 00:36:45.329
when he said that, wow, an ironic effect,

00:36:46.578 --> 00:36:50.745
or to deny death, may be that
we are the first form of life

00:36:51.988 --> 00:36:53.669
to have the ignominious distinction

00:36:53.669 --> 00:36:56.690
of being responsible for our extinction.

00:36:56.690 --> 00:36:57.729
Alright, having said that, though,

00:36:57.729 --> 00:36:59.593
let me close on a more positive note,

00:36:59.593 --> 00:37:00.983
and just point out,
(crowd laughing)

00:37:00.983 --> 00:37:05.043
usually, I stop now, and
I go, thank you very much.

00:37:05.043 --> 00:37:06.611
On a more positive note, though,

00:37:06.611 --> 00:37:09.452
human beings, we have a good
track record, historically,

00:37:09.452 --> 00:37:11.382
of extricating ourselves

00:37:11.382 --> 00:37:13.777
from some very difficult circumstances,

00:37:13.777 --> 00:37:17.846
once we understand what underlies them.

00:37:17.846 --> 00:37:21.158
In the middle ages, when people
were dropping like flies,

00:37:21.158 --> 00:37:22.421
from the plague,

00:37:22.421 --> 00:37:24.830
when we thought that it
was caused by evil spirits,

00:37:24.830 --> 00:37:26.792
we really didn't get anywhere.

00:37:26.792 --> 00:37:29.909
On the other hand, when we
realized that it was bacteria,

00:37:29.909 --> 00:37:33.096
then, we were able to develop penicillin,

00:37:33.096 --> 00:37:36.094
and that led to modern medicine.

00:37:36.094 --> 00:37:38.390
Similarly, what I would like to think,

00:37:38.390 --> 00:37:40.701
even if this appears naively optimistic,

00:37:40.701 --> 00:37:44.990
is that if we could
collectively come to recognize

00:37:44.990 --> 00:37:46.860
the incredible problems,

00:37:46.860 --> 00:37:50.934
that excessive death denial has produced,

00:37:50.934 --> 00:37:54.859
then, maybe, we can
also collectively deploy

00:37:54.859 --> 00:37:58.618
our remarkable creativity, and ingenuity,

00:37:58.618 --> 00:38:02.687
in order to nudge our
species into a more benign,

00:38:02.687 --> 00:38:05.189
or maybe, even more benevolent direction.

00:38:05.189 --> 00:38:08.228
I like how Camus put it,
"Come to terms with death.

00:38:08.228 --> 00:38:10.767
"Thereafter, anything is possible."

00:38:10.767 --> 00:38:12.065
Maybe an overstatement,

00:38:12.065 --> 00:38:15.594
but no harm in using this as
a standard to approximate.

00:38:15.594 --> 00:38:16.427
Thank you very much.

00:38:16.427 --> 00:38:20.105
(crowd applauding)

00:38:20.105 --> 00:38:21.135
- And such, you said,

00:38:21.135 --> 00:38:24.360
we thought we should discuss
this issue of suicide

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:26.800
at this meeting, because it is something,

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:28.353
which is almost certainly,

00:38:28.353 --> 00:38:32.516
had a major bearing on
history of our own species.

00:38:32.516 --> 00:38:37.247
I've shown the panel from
a late Roman ivory casket,

00:38:37.247 --> 00:38:39.130
which is in the British Museum.

00:38:39.130 --> 00:38:42.977
You'll see, it shows two very
different examples of humans,

00:38:42.977 --> 00:38:46.436
who brought death on
themselves deliberately.

00:38:46.436 --> 00:38:49.344
Jesus, who had no desire to stop living,

00:38:49.344 --> 00:38:53.054
but who believed his death
would benefit all mankind.

00:38:53.054 --> 00:38:56.496
And then, Judas, who had no
thought of benefiting others,

00:38:56.496 --> 00:39:00.385
(stammers) but assumed that his own death

00:39:00.385 --> 00:39:05.076
would at least put an end to
his own intolerable guilt.

00:39:05.076 --> 00:39:08.857
Suicide used to be called self-murder.

00:39:08.857 --> 00:39:11.227
It may seem hard to associate,

00:39:11.227 --> 00:39:15.299
harsher to say, to associate
suicide with murder.

00:39:15.299 --> 00:39:16.132
But, if we're looking

00:39:16.132 --> 00:39:18.718
for the evolutionary
antecedents of suicide,

00:39:18.718 --> 00:39:22.869
I think this does, in fact,
get us off on the right foot.

00:39:22.869 --> 00:39:25.702
Humans have always been murderers.

00:39:26.639 --> 00:39:28.446
First, of course,

00:39:28.446 --> 00:39:31.498
they've been killers
of other living beings.

00:39:31.498 --> 00:39:34.539
First, of course, they were
killers of animal prey,

00:39:34.539 --> 00:39:36.674
for food, and everybody in the community

00:39:36.674 --> 00:39:39.790
would've been involved directly, in that.

00:39:39.790 --> 00:39:43.151
But, they were also killers
of other human beings.

00:39:43.151 --> 00:39:45.666
Not everyone would've
had firsthand experience

00:39:45.666 --> 00:39:47.325
of assassination.

00:39:47.325 --> 00:39:50.178
But, everyone would've known
about it, and talked about it,

00:39:50.178 --> 00:39:52.425
and note, celebrated it.

00:39:52.425 --> 00:39:55.045
And then, the idea dawned.

00:39:55.045 --> 00:39:59.846
Here's how psychiatrist
Erwin Stengel has put it.

00:39:59.846 --> 00:40:03.466
"At some stage of evolution,
man must have discovered,

00:40:03.466 --> 00:40:06.475
"that he can kill not only
animals and fellow-men,

00:40:06.475 --> 00:40:08.589
"but also himself.

00:40:08.589 --> 00:40:11.226
"It can be assumed that
life has never since

00:40:11.226 --> 00:40:13.047
"been the same for him."

00:40:13.047 --> 00:40:15.961
But, I think it wasn't
so much the discovery,

00:40:15.961 --> 00:40:18.764
that he can kill himself,
that would've changed things.

00:40:18.764 --> 00:40:21.763
It was the discovery
of what killing himself

00:40:21.763 --> 00:40:23.313
would've amounted to,

00:40:23.313 --> 00:40:24.735
that it would've amounted to

00:40:24.735 --> 00:40:27.835
removing himself from the world.

00:40:27.835 --> 00:40:30.418
A human could choose not to be.

00:40:31.654 --> 00:40:34.246
That's why non-human
animals don't, and can't,

00:40:34.246 --> 00:40:35.731
commit suicide.

00:40:35.731 --> 00:40:38.705
At any rate, even if
they do kill themselves,

00:40:38.705 --> 00:40:40.864
as perhaps, these whales did,

00:40:40.864 --> 00:40:42.832
we shouldn't call it suicide.

00:40:42.832 --> 00:40:46.556
Though, that BBC headline
clearly did suggest we might.

00:40:46.556 --> 00:40:49.165
The whales can't have been choosing death,

00:40:49.165 --> 00:40:50.683
because, so far, as we know,

00:40:50.683 --> 00:40:54.804
they haven't discovered what death means.

00:40:54.804 --> 00:40:57.086
But, humans, of course, have done.

00:40:57.086 --> 00:40:59.037
Humans can choose death,

00:40:59.037 --> 00:41:01.986
knowing pretty well what it'll
mean for them personally.

00:41:01.986 --> 00:41:04.041
Now, I think Stengel's right to say,

00:41:04.041 --> 00:41:08.205
that this discovery has
been transformative.

00:41:08.205 --> 00:41:12.069
But, we still have to ask,
transformative in just what ways?

00:41:12.069 --> 00:41:14.411
And if we're thinking
about human evolution,

00:41:14.411 --> 00:41:18.080
the question must be,
what effects, good or bad,

00:41:18.080 --> 00:41:21.997
did this discovery have
on biological survival?

00:41:23.319 --> 00:41:26.288
Other kinds of killing
can clearly be adaptive.

00:41:26.288 --> 00:41:30.978
It's easier to explain the
survival advantages of hunting.

00:41:30.978 --> 00:41:34.180
It's not difficult to explain
the advantages of war,

00:41:34.180 --> 00:41:35.180
or homicide.

00:41:36.078 --> 00:41:39.358
But, common sense would seem
to say that self-killing

00:41:39.358 --> 00:41:42.641
must be the ultimately
disadvantageous act,

00:41:42.641 --> 00:41:45.671
a sure path to genetic oblivion.

00:41:45.671 --> 00:41:48.161
Yes, the stark fact is,

00:41:48.161 --> 00:41:51.670
that suicide is alarmingly
common, right across the world.

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:52.950
Someone in the United States

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:55.830
kills themselves every 12 minutes.

00:41:55.830 --> 00:41:57.247
That's 120 a day.

00:41:58.088 --> 00:42:01.129
Across the world, more
people die from suicide,

00:42:01.129 --> 00:42:04.379
than all wars, and homicides, combined.

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:07.631
We surely have to ask, then,

00:42:07.631 --> 00:42:11.214
is suicide biologically
adaptive after all?

00:42:12.182 --> 00:42:14.019
Well, the answer's not going to be simple.

00:42:14.019 --> 00:42:15.918
As I implied with my first slide,

00:42:15.918 --> 00:42:17.706
I think we need to distinguish

00:42:17.706 --> 00:42:20.547
two rather different kinds of suicide.

00:42:20.547 --> 00:42:23.006
And we can call them as their kind did,

00:42:23.006 --> 00:42:26.436
altruistic suicide and egoistic suicide.

00:42:26.436 --> 00:42:28.544
And I want to suggest a correspond

00:42:28.544 --> 00:42:33.318
to two rather different
conceptions of what death does.

00:42:33.318 --> 00:42:35.660
The first, and simplest conception,

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:39.782
is that death results in the
annihilation of the body.

00:42:39.782 --> 00:42:42.049
The dead person is no longer an actor

00:42:42.049 --> 00:42:44.702
in the physical, or social world.

00:42:44.702 --> 00:42:46.403
And corresponding to this,

00:42:46.403 --> 00:42:50.013
when people choose to bring
about their own death,

00:42:50.013 --> 00:42:53.252
they're, maybe, trying to
make things better for others,

00:42:53.252 --> 00:42:56.344
by giving up their own bodily presence.

00:42:56.344 --> 00:42:57.522
Jesus died on the cross,

00:42:57.522 --> 00:43:01.382
in the hope of becoming
the savior of all mankind.

00:43:01.382 --> 00:43:04.294
Or, for a more straightforward
example, Captain Oates,

00:43:04.294 --> 00:43:06.293
stumbled out to die in the snow,

00:43:06.293 --> 00:43:08.366
in the hope of relieving the burden

00:43:08.366 --> 00:43:12.876
for the remaining members
of Scott's polar expedition.

00:43:12.876 --> 00:43:15.938
Altruistic suicide, we can call that.

00:43:15.938 --> 00:43:18.916
But, could this kind
of suicide be adaptive?

00:43:18.916 --> 00:43:20.254
It certainly could be,

00:43:20.254 --> 00:43:23.885
provided it benefits the
subject's kin, or social group.

00:43:23.885 --> 00:43:24.924
In fact, it's possible,

00:43:24.924 --> 00:43:28.582
that a propensity for altruistic suicide,

00:43:28.582 --> 00:43:31.722
has been selected in humans,
in rather the same way

00:43:31.722 --> 00:43:34.091
that something like it has been selected

00:43:34.091 --> 00:43:36.398
in the social instance.

00:43:36.398 --> 00:43:39.608
So, maybe, humans are
genetically predisposed,

00:43:39.608 --> 00:43:42.581
like ants or bees, to
sacrifice themselves,

00:43:42.581 --> 00:43:44.237
for the common good,

00:43:44.237 --> 00:43:47.288
in times of famine, or plague, or war,

00:43:47.288 --> 00:43:49.096
or simply, when they become too old

00:43:49.096 --> 00:43:51.517
and decrepit to carry on.

00:43:51.517 --> 00:43:54.103
But now, let's look at
another kind of suicide,

00:43:54.103 --> 00:43:56.471
perhaps, corresponding
to a second conception

00:43:56.471 --> 00:43:58.204
of what death does.

00:43:58.204 --> 00:44:02.250
It says that death results in
the annihilation of the mind.

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:05.745
The dead person is no longer
a thinker, or a feeler.

00:44:05.745 --> 00:44:08.194
In correspondence to this conception,

00:44:08.194 --> 00:44:10.055
when people kill themselves,

00:44:10.055 --> 00:44:13.837
they're, maybe, trying to make
things better for themselves,

00:44:13.837 --> 00:44:17.056
by giving up on their
own conscious presence.

00:44:17.056 --> 00:44:19.575
Judas Iscariot sought conscious oblivion,

00:44:19.575 --> 00:44:24.254
because he could not live with
his internal sense of shame.

00:44:24.254 --> 00:44:27.282
This young couple could not bear the pain

00:44:27.282 --> 00:44:29.922
of being forbidden by
their families, to marry.

00:44:29.922 --> 00:44:32.385
This is egoistic suicide.

00:44:32.385 --> 00:44:35.463
And this, in many ways,
they're absolute opposite

00:44:35.463 --> 00:44:36.975
of altruistic suicide.

00:44:36.975 --> 00:44:39.146
Far from hoping to benefit others,

00:44:39.146 --> 00:44:42.135
these self-killers are
motivated, primarily,

00:44:42.135 --> 00:44:43.523
by self interest.

00:44:43.523 --> 00:44:46.205
They either don't care
about the effect on others,

00:44:46.205 --> 00:44:50.434
or, sometimes, they even
intend some kind of vengeance.

00:44:50.434 --> 00:44:52.195
And whether they intend it, or not,

00:44:52.195 --> 00:44:56.244
the effects on family and
friends are often devastating.

00:44:56.244 --> 00:44:59.533
Now, here's the problem from
an evolutionary point of view.

00:44:59.533 --> 00:45:03.861
The fact is, that 90 percent
of suicides are egotistical.

00:45:03.861 --> 00:45:06.374
The World Federation of
Mental Health, for example,

00:45:06.374 --> 00:45:10.537
reports that the most common
situations, or life events,

00:45:10.537 --> 00:45:12.980
that might cause suicidal thoughts,

00:45:12.980 --> 00:45:15.070
that don't have to do
with helping other people,

00:45:15.070 --> 00:45:19.313
that grief, sexual abuse,
financial problems, remorse,

00:45:19.313 --> 00:45:22.962
rejection, relationship
breakup, and unemployment.

00:45:22.962 --> 00:45:24.831
And anthropologist, Charles MacDonald,

00:45:24.831 --> 00:45:28.703
having surveyed suicide across
the whole world, concludes,

00:45:28.703 --> 00:45:32.322
"A cross-cultural comparison
shows that grief over,

00:45:32.322 --> 00:45:35.088
"and conflict between
closely related people,

00:45:35.088 --> 00:45:38.147
"together with sheer
physical pain and discomfort,

00:45:38.147 --> 00:45:40.069
"cause, or promote suicide

00:45:40.069 --> 00:45:42.539
"more often than any other circumstances.

00:45:42.539 --> 00:45:46.129
"The suicide simply
wants to stop hurting."

00:45:46.129 --> 00:45:49.142
What their egoistic
suicide wants to achieve,

00:45:49.142 --> 00:45:52.370
is basically self-euthanasia.

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:55.011
Well, could this be adaptive?

00:45:55.011 --> 00:45:57.130
Though, how could it possibly be?

00:45:57.130 --> 00:46:00.047
Most egoistical suicides are young.

00:46:00.920 --> 00:46:01.896
Across the world,

00:46:01.896 --> 00:46:04.223
it's the second-most
common cause of death,

00:46:04.223 --> 00:46:06.043
amongst teenagers.

00:46:06.043 --> 00:46:08.452
If they've not died by their own hand,

00:46:08.452 --> 00:46:10.533
this couple hadn't died by their own hand,

00:46:10.533 --> 00:46:12.911
they would, almost certainly,
have got over the hurt,

00:46:12.911 --> 00:46:16.861
and gone on to make a
success of their lives.

00:46:16.861 --> 00:46:18.341
Egoistic suicides,

00:46:18.341 --> 00:46:21.461
will end not only their
own biological fitness,

00:46:21.461 --> 00:46:23.952
but those other related individuals, too.

00:46:23.952 --> 00:46:25.661
So, what's going on?

00:46:25.661 --> 00:46:29.072
Why do these tragic deaths
happen so frequently?

00:46:29.072 --> 00:46:31.301
I think the answer's all too obvious.

00:46:31.301 --> 00:46:33.361
Humans, and humans alone,

00:46:33.361 --> 00:46:35.811
understand that by killing themselves,

00:46:35.811 --> 00:46:39.483
they can, indeed, stop the hurting.

00:46:39.483 --> 00:46:41.152
So, there must be circumstances,

00:46:41.152 --> 00:46:45.462
when they may well look on
suicide as a rational act.

00:46:45.462 --> 00:46:48.095
They feel sad, or jealous, or unloved,

00:46:48.095 --> 00:46:50.475
or inadequate, or whatever.

00:46:50.475 --> 00:46:54.103
These are feelings that
death will make go away.

00:46:54.103 --> 00:46:57.020
Nothing hurts less than being dead.

00:46:58.004 --> 00:47:02.262
In Hamlet's (stammers)
sorry, that once more,

00:47:02.262 --> 00:47:05.515
as the poetry of suicide,
continue to reminds us,

00:47:05.515 --> 00:47:09.303
this solution to the hurting
may not only be rational,

00:47:09.303 --> 00:47:12.533
it must, often be, relatively easy.

00:47:12.533 --> 00:47:14.992
In Hamlet's notorious soliloquy,

00:47:14.992 --> 00:47:17.462
"Who would bear the
whips and scorns of time,

00:47:17.462 --> 00:47:20.405
"The oppressor's wrong,
the proud man's contumely,

00:47:20.405 --> 00:47:24.007
"The pangs of despised
love, the law's delay,

00:47:24.007 --> 00:47:26.898
"When he himself might his quietus make

00:47:26.898 --> 00:47:28.366
"With a bare bodkin?"

00:47:28.366 --> 00:47:29.399
A dagger.

00:47:29.399 --> 00:47:31.208
As some would recognize is,

00:47:31.208 --> 00:47:34.557
there's an unfortunate
truth about being human,

00:47:34.557 --> 00:47:37.997
probably more true of humans,
than any other animal,

00:47:37.997 --> 00:47:41.247
and it is that hurting is part of life.

00:47:42.237 --> 00:47:45.308
The part of Ceasuri
Provezi, said it explicitly,

00:47:45.308 --> 00:47:49.238
everyone, every human, has
a good reason for suicide.

00:47:49.238 --> 00:47:51.912
The philosopher, Wittgenstein,
once told a friend,

00:47:51.912 --> 00:47:54.898
that all his life, there
had hardly been a day,

00:47:54.898 --> 00:47:58.120
in which he hadn't thought
suicide a possibility.

00:47:58.120 --> 00:48:01.910
More typically, among today's
American high school students,

00:48:01.910 --> 00:48:05.480
60 percent say they've
considered killing themselves.

00:48:05.480 --> 00:48:08.151
14 percent have thought
about it seriously,

00:48:08.151 --> 00:48:09.660
in the last year.

00:48:09.660 --> 00:48:12.391
And five percent have attempted it.

00:48:12.391 --> 00:48:15.532
That's more than one
million students a year.

00:48:15.532 --> 00:48:19.340
Susan Sontag has written,
"How thin the line,

00:48:19.340 --> 00:48:23.070
"between the will to
live, and the will to die.

00:48:23.070 --> 00:48:25.122
"How about a hole?" she asks.

00:48:25.122 --> 00:48:28.329
"A really deep hole, which
you put in a public place,

00:48:28.329 --> 00:48:29.888
"for general use.

00:48:29.888 --> 00:48:33.282
"In Manhattan, say, at the
corner of Seventieth and Fifth.

00:48:33.282 --> 00:48:37.179
"A sign beside the hole
reads: 4:00 PM to 8:00 PM,

00:48:37.179 --> 00:48:41.277
"Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays, suicide permitted.

00:48:41.277 --> 00:48:42.110
"Just that.

00:48:42.110 --> 00:48:43.355
"A sign.

00:48:43.355 --> 00:48:45.053
"Why, surely people would jump

00:48:45.053 --> 00:48:48.191
"who had hardly thought of it before."

00:48:48.191 --> 00:48:51.082
As I said, it's not only
rational, sometimes,

00:48:51.082 --> 00:48:52.901
but it's also very easy.

00:48:52.901 --> 00:48:55.110
Now, this is a CARTA symposium.

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:57.101
And we want to understand how humans,

00:48:57.101 --> 00:48:58.950
against all the odds, perhaps,

00:48:58.950 --> 00:49:02.274
have, in the end, survived and prospered.

00:49:02.274 --> 00:49:03.107
And it looks as though,

00:49:03.107 --> 00:49:06.346
suicide might be a very significant drain

00:49:06.346 --> 00:49:09.173
on the fitness of our ancestors.

00:49:09.173 --> 00:49:11.440
Looks as though it might
have been a major downside

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:13.834
of their growing sufficiently clever,

00:49:13.834 --> 00:49:16.321
to understand their own mortality.

00:49:16.321 --> 00:49:18.963
The very sequence Ajit talked about.

00:49:18.963 --> 00:49:19.796
It wouldn't have been bad,

00:49:19.796 --> 00:49:22.530
because (stammers) dangerous,
because they feared death,

00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:25.142
but because they were attracted to it.

00:49:25.142 --> 00:49:26.912
But, surely, natural selection, then,

00:49:26.912 --> 00:49:29.055
would've sorted this out long ago.

00:49:29.055 --> 00:49:33.028
Why haven't humans evolved to
have better innate defenses

00:49:33.028 --> 00:49:36.117
against suicide, built into their minds?

00:49:36.117 --> 00:49:38.717
Well, of course, Ajit thinks they have.

00:49:38.717 --> 00:49:41.097
When reality becomes too much to bear,

00:49:41.097 --> 00:49:42.930
people simply deny it.

00:49:44.235 --> 00:49:47.903
But, I confess, I don't see
this working as he says,

00:49:47.903 --> 00:49:50.013
or, at least, not in these contexts.

00:49:50.013 --> 00:49:52.379
I see no evidence that humans have evolved

00:49:52.379 --> 00:49:55.499
to have any kind of natural immunity

00:49:55.499 --> 00:49:58.520
to what I've called the lure of death.

00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:01.420
To the contrary, I'm led
to think that in the past,

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:04.990
if not today, suicide might
have spread like measles,

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:07.768
in an unprotected population.

00:50:07.768 --> 00:50:09.628
In fact, measles is a surprisingly,

00:50:09.628 --> 00:50:12.188
alarmingly apposite analogy,

00:50:12.188 --> 00:50:17.096
because the suicide meme
happens to be highly infectious.

00:50:17.096 --> 00:50:18.753
It jumps from mind to mind,

00:50:18.753 --> 00:50:21.650
resulting in the
well-documented phenomenon

00:50:21.650 --> 00:50:23.740
of copycat suicides.

00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:27.441
As Durkheim wrote, "Suicide
is very contagious.

00:50:27.441 --> 00:50:29.609
"There is the well-known
story of the fifteen patients

00:50:29.609 --> 00:50:33.191
"who hung themselves, in
swift succession, in 1772,

00:50:33.191 --> 00:50:37.071
"from the same hook, in a
dark passage of the hospital."

00:50:37.071 --> 00:50:40.673
Suicide contagion has been
dubbed the Werther effect,

00:50:40.673 --> 00:50:43.521
after the hero of Goethe's novel,

00:50:43.521 --> 00:50:46.557
The Sorrows of Young Werther.

00:50:46.557 --> 00:50:48.861
In the novel, Werther kills himself,

00:50:48.861 --> 00:50:52.059
after falling hopelessly in
love with a married woman.

00:50:52.059 --> 00:50:54.959
Following its publication in 1774,

00:50:54.959 --> 00:50:58.390
there were literally hundreds
of copycat deaths in Germany.

00:50:58.390 --> 00:51:01.911
Recent researchers confirmed
just how strong the effect is.

00:51:01.911 --> 00:51:05.922
Every time a celebrity
suicide is given exposure

00:51:05.922 --> 00:51:09.570
in a newspaper, or TV,
the copycats follow.

00:51:09.570 --> 00:51:11.834
It's estimated that
Marilyn Monroe's death,

00:51:11.834 --> 00:51:16.001
in August 1962, was responsible
for 200 actual suicides,

00:51:16.852 --> 00:51:17.865
within a month.

00:51:17.865 --> 00:51:20.144
After a popular South Korean actress,

00:51:20.144 --> 00:51:24.695
hung herself in 2008,
suicides jumped 66 percent

00:51:24.695 --> 00:51:25.583
that month,

00:51:25.583 --> 00:51:27.781
with young, hanging victims accounting

00:51:27.781 --> 00:51:30.350
for the most of the increase.

00:51:30.350 --> 00:51:33.411
But, 66 percent, that's nothing.

00:51:33.411 --> 00:51:35.319
There are some parts of the world today,

00:51:35.319 --> 00:51:38.877
where rates of suicide are ten
times the average elsewhere.

00:51:38.877 --> 00:51:42.865
And this turned out to be,
largely to do, with copying.

00:51:42.865 --> 00:51:46.342
Among these happy people,
on the island of Palawan,

00:51:46.342 --> 00:51:49.344
in the Philippines, MacDonald's
research has documented

00:51:49.344 --> 00:51:52.800
waves of suicides, spreading
through small villages.

00:51:52.800 --> 00:51:53.953
The question becomes, then,

00:51:53.953 --> 00:51:56.893
how prevalent was suicide
amongst our ancestors,

00:51:56.893 --> 00:51:59.244
say, 50,000 years ago?

00:51:59.244 --> 00:52:01.746
I don't think any paleoanthropologist

00:52:01.746 --> 00:52:03.856
has ever thought to ask.

00:52:03.856 --> 00:52:06.256
But, assuming humans, must by then,

00:52:06.256 --> 00:52:08.988
have required an understanding of death,

00:52:08.988 --> 00:52:12.836
we can be quite sure there were suicides.

00:52:12.836 --> 00:52:15.517
And let's remember, times were harsh,

00:52:15.517 --> 00:52:18.104
in the icy climate of central Europe.

00:52:18.104 --> 00:52:20.783
There would've been plenty
to be unhappy about,

00:52:20.783 --> 00:52:23.287
or think we shouldn't
allow the possibility

00:52:23.287 --> 00:52:24.574
that there were, indeed,

00:52:24.574 --> 00:52:27.192
recurrent plagues of egoistic suicide,

00:52:27.192 --> 00:52:30.562
with rates topping anything we see today.

00:52:30.562 --> 00:52:32.553
Well, if this is true,

00:52:32.553 --> 00:52:34.536
if there were these plagues of suicide,

00:52:34.536 --> 00:52:38.047
and I think it's a genuine,
scientific possibility,

00:52:38.047 --> 00:52:41.364
what could, and did,
bring it under control?

00:52:41.364 --> 00:52:45.315
Assuming humans have never
evolved adequate natural immunity

00:52:45.315 --> 00:52:48.716
to suicide, antidote, whatever it was,

00:52:48.716 --> 00:52:51.088
must have been cultural.

00:52:51.088 --> 00:52:53.337
And here, I have to say,
the picture's complicated,

00:52:53.337 --> 00:52:55.819
and not well-researched.

00:52:55.819 --> 00:52:58.388
Apparently, some of the
cultural barriers to suicide

00:52:58.388 --> 00:53:01.090
are, indeed, in plain view.

00:53:01.090 --> 00:53:03.600
In historical times, religious authorities

00:53:03.600 --> 00:53:07.336
have regularly issued
an athamus against it.

00:53:07.336 --> 00:53:09.858
Medieval Christianity
decreed that self-murderers

00:53:09.858 --> 00:53:11.568
would go to Hell.

00:53:11.568 --> 00:53:15.014
Victims would not be given
a decent burial, but rather,

00:53:15.014 --> 00:53:17.770
be buried at the crossroads, at night,

00:53:17.770 --> 00:53:20.513
with a stake through the heart.

00:53:20.513 --> 00:53:22.528
In many countries, attempted suicide

00:53:22.528 --> 00:53:26.283
has also been made a crime,
under the common law.

00:53:26.283 --> 00:53:27.485
In the United Kingdom,

00:53:27.485 --> 00:53:31.652
attempted suicide was not
decriminalized, until 1961.

00:53:33.075 --> 00:53:37.242
In the ten years, pre-1961,
there were 6,000 prosecutions,

00:53:38.683 --> 00:53:42.850
5,400 attempted suicides were
filed guilty, and imprisoned,

00:53:44.125 --> 00:53:44.958
or fined.

00:53:45.863 --> 00:53:48.722
It was common practice
in the 1950s, in Britain,

00:53:48.722 --> 00:53:51.212
to have a policeman,
sitting at the bedside,

00:53:51.212 --> 00:53:55.273
of an unconscious patient,
in accident and emergency,

00:53:55.273 --> 00:53:59.440
waiting to interview the patient,
when he, or she, revived.

00:54:01.057 --> 00:54:03.501
There've also been attempts to
limit the spread of suicide,

00:54:03.501 --> 00:54:07.039
the suicide meme, by
limiting exposure to it.

00:54:07.039 --> 00:54:10.621
In Europe, after the
effect of Goethe's book

00:54:10.621 --> 00:54:14.208
became apparent, was soon
banned in several countries.

00:54:14.208 --> 00:54:16.420
In Germany, it was even forbidden to dress

00:54:16.420 --> 00:54:20.527
like young Werther, in blue
coat, and yellow trousers.

00:54:20.527 --> 00:54:22.178
In most countries today,

00:54:22.178 --> 00:54:23.737
there are restrict press guidelines,

00:54:23.737 --> 00:54:26.578
intended to play down
the reporting of suicide,

00:54:26.578 --> 00:54:28.575
to keep it off the front page,

00:54:28.575 --> 00:54:31.678
and to avoid sensational headlines.

00:54:31.678 --> 00:54:34.105
So, we've had suicidal
acts being punished,

00:54:34.105 --> 00:54:36.525
and information about them suppressed.

00:54:36.525 --> 00:54:39.567
Do these measures actually work?

00:54:39.567 --> 00:54:41.579
My guess, I think there's reason to think,

00:54:41.579 --> 00:54:43.726
they actually, probably, do.

00:54:43.726 --> 00:54:47.044
Or, at any rate, there's no
reason to think that they don't.

00:54:47.044 --> 00:54:51.244
But, surely, more focused
methods ought to work as well.

00:54:51.244 --> 00:54:53.644
In place of punishment, or censorship,

00:54:53.644 --> 00:54:57.267
why not try to fight meme with meme?

00:54:57.267 --> 00:55:00.105
Why not oppose a destructive mind virus,

00:55:00.105 --> 00:55:02.494
with a redemptive one?

00:55:02.494 --> 00:55:06.633
What should we tell people,
who want to kill themselves?

00:55:06.633 --> 00:55:08.421
The English priest, Chad Varah,

00:55:08.421 --> 00:55:11.770
founded the Samaritans, in 1954,

00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:15.262
a group dedicated to
talking suicides down,

00:55:15.262 --> 00:55:17.462
with words of reassurance.

00:55:17.462 --> 00:55:21.581
The message, there is hope,
may seem to verge on the banal,

00:55:21.581 --> 00:55:24.213
but, in fact, it's the
one message we can give

00:55:24.213 --> 00:55:25.566
with confidence.

00:55:25.566 --> 00:55:28.785
Research shows, that in
nine cases out of ten,

00:55:28.785 --> 00:55:31.017
the hurt isn't going to last.

00:55:31.017 --> 00:55:35.184
Here's Daniel Gilbert, who
actually quoted off of the book,

00:55:36.026 --> 00:55:38.078
Stumbling on Happiness,

00:55:38.078 --> 00:55:39.788
"Few of us can accurately gauge

00:55:39.788 --> 00:55:42.020
"how we will feel tomorrow, or next week.

00:55:42.020 --> 00:55:45.071
"We expect to feel devastated,
if our spouse leaves us,

00:55:45.071 --> 00:55:49.134
"or if we get passed over
for a big promotion at work.

00:55:49.134 --> 00:55:51.412
"But, when things like that do happen,

00:55:51.412 --> 00:55:54.369
"it's soon, 'She never was right for me,'

00:55:54.369 --> 00:55:58.038
"or, 'Actually, I needed more
free time for my family.'

00:55:58.038 --> 00:56:00.680
"People mistakenly expect such blows

00:56:00.680 --> 00:56:04.353
"to be much more devastating
than they turn out to be."

00:56:04.353 --> 00:56:06.733
And since it's a pessimism bias,

00:56:06.733 --> 00:56:08.864
we think things are
going to be really bad,

00:56:08.864 --> 00:56:12.384
so bad, that we can do
nothing, but end our lives.

00:56:12.384 --> 00:56:14.683
But, the message of this
research, I suppose,

00:56:14.683 --> 00:56:16.814
is, don't jump now,

00:56:16.814 --> 00:56:21.071
because it's not what your
future self would choose.

00:56:21.071 --> 00:56:23.362
But, have we had to wait
for a Harvard psychologist

00:56:23.362 --> 00:56:24.851
to tell us this?

00:56:24.851 --> 00:56:26.012
No, thankfully not.

00:56:26.012 --> 00:56:27.411
The message is implicit.

00:56:27.411 --> 00:56:31.169
Perhaps, actually presumably,
for a good reason.

00:56:31.169 --> 00:56:34.931
In much of the hand-me-down
wisdom of our old cultures,

00:56:34.931 --> 00:56:38.240
in stories, and songs,
and proverbs, and so on.

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:40.083
And the good news for our species,

00:56:40.083 --> 00:56:43.714
is that on the whole, with
too many dreadful exceptions,

00:56:43.714 --> 00:56:46.712
hope can, and does, win out.

00:56:46.712 --> 00:56:48.782
And I think that's what basically

00:56:48.782 --> 00:56:53.463
has taken us out of the ice
ages, to where we are today.

00:56:53.463 --> 00:56:54.526
Okay.

00:56:54.526 --> 00:56:57.286
This is the closing talk of the symposium.

00:56:57.286 --> 00:57:01.764
We've heard a lot today, about
what a bad thing death is.

00:57:01.764 --> 00:57:03.033
We haven't actually heard much

00:57:03.033 --> 00:57:06.411
about what a good thing life
is, which is, in the end,

00:57:06.411 --> 00:57:08.762
of course, the whole point.

00:57:08.762 --> 00:57:11.470
So, I'll finish with a
passage from George Borrow's

00:57:11.470 --> 00:57:14.509
autobiographical novel, Lavengro,

00:57:14.509 --> 00:57:17.084
which echoes some of the things
actually Sheldon was saying.

00:57:17.084 --> 00:57:20.163
As Borrow tells it, he's
been reading Goethe,

00:57:20.163 --> 00:57:22.412
and it's an autobiography,
I think he had been,

00:57:22.412 --> 00:57:25.550
and he's toying with the idea of suicide.

00:57:25.550 --> 00:57:29.665
He gets into conversation
with a Romany gypsy, Jasper,

00:57:29.665 --> 00:57:31.967
who he's befriended on his travels.

00:57:31.967 --> 00:57:34.065
I'll read a passage from the novel.

00:57:34.065 --> 00:57:36.335
"'What is your opinion of death?' said I,

00:57:36.335 --> 00:57:39.014
"as I sat down beside him.

00:57:39.014 --> 00:57:41.594
"Jasper replies, 'Life is sweet, brother.

00:57:41.594 --> 00:57:43.835
"'Who would wish to die?'

00:57:43.835 --> 00:57:46.349
"'I would wish to die,'" says Borrow.

00:57:46.349 --> 00:57:48.978
"'You talk like a fool,' says Jasper.

00:57:48.978 --> 00:57:51.599
"'Wish to die, indeed.

00:57:51.599 --> 00:57:54.949
"'There's night and day,
brother, both sweet things;

00:57:54.949 --> 00:57:59.116
"'sun, moon, and stars,
brother, all sweet things.

00:58:00.220 --> 00:58:02.397
"'There's the wind on the heath, brother;

00:58:02.397 --> 00:58:07.006
"'if I could only feel that,
I would gladly live forever.'"

00:58:07.006 --> 00:58:08.326
Well, this painting is, in fact,

00:58:08.326 --> 00:58:10.425
called The Wind on the Heath.

00:58:10.425 --> 00:58:14.504
And I think the good news,
is that we've all been there.

00:58:14.504 --> 00:58:15.629
Well, thank you.

00:58:15.629 --> 00:58:17.727
(crowd applauding)

00:58:17.727 --> 00:58:21.477
(mid-tempo electronic music)

